Problem 1.

1. Create a training set containing a random sample of 800 observations, and a test set containing the remaining observations.

set.seed(1)
train = sample(1:nrow(OJ), 800)
test = -train

SVMs

2. Fit a support vector classier to the training data using cost = 0.01, with Purchase as the response and the other variables as predictors. Use the summary() function to produce summary statistics, and describe the results obtained.

svmfit=svm(Purchase~., data=OJ[train,], kernel="linear", cost=0.01, scale=FALSE)

8. Overall, which approach seems to give the best results on this data?

  • It appears that the svm with a polynomial kernal with cost 0.01 and degree 2 did the best job predicting on the test data however the svm with a linear kernal and a cost of 4.01 appears to be a close second.

Problem 2.

Principal Components Analysis

9. Perform PCA on these data.

attach(USArrests)
names(USArrests)
## [1] "Murder"   "Assault"  "UrbanPop" "Rape"
pr.out=prcomp(USArrests, scale=TRUE)
biplot(pr.out, scale=0)

10. Create a scree plot to examine what number of principal components contain a majority of the information in the data set.

pr.var=pr.out$sdev^2
pve=pr.var/sum(pr.var)

plot(pve, xlab="Principal  Component", ylab="Proportion of Variance Explained", ylim=c(0,1),type="b")

plot(cumsum(pve), xlab="Principal  Component", ylab="Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained", ylim=c(0,1),type="b")

11. Report the PVE values. Based on these and your plot in (10), choose a number of PCs to use that is less than p.Be sure to explain your choice.

  • Considering the elbow in the above graphs around 2-3 PCs and the fact that the first two PCs are able to explain almost 87% of the variability so I think 2 PCs is a good choice.
pve
## [1] 0.62006039 0.24744129 0.08914080 0.04335752

Ridge Regression

18. Fit a ridge regression model on the training set, with ?? chosen by cross-validation. Report the test error obtained.

x=model.matrix(Apps~.,College)[,-1]
y=College$Apps

set.seed(1)
train=sample(1:nrow(x), nrow(x)/2)
test=(-train)
y.test=y[test]

cv.out=cv.glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha=0)
plot(cv.out)

bestlam=cv.out$lambda.min
bestlam
## [1] 405.8404
grid=10^seq(10,-2,length=100)
ridge.mod=glmnet(x[train ,],y[train],alpha=0,lambda=grid,thresh=1e-12)

ridge.pred=predict(ridge.mod,s=bestlam ,newx=x[test,])
mean((ridge.pred-y.test)^2)
## [1] 976647.8
